83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
A-Engrossed
House Bill 4093
Ordered by the House February 13
Including House Amendments dated February 13
Sponsored by Representative NELSON, Senators GELSER BLOUIN, MANNING JR, Representatives CHAICHI,
CHOTZEN, MUNOZ, RIEKE SMITH, WISE, Senators FREDERICK, GORSEK; Representatives ANDERSEN,
ISADORE, MCDONALD, WALTERS, Senator PATTERSON (Presession filed.)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: The Act makes new laws with respect to people with disabilities. (Flesch Readability
Score: 64.9).
Directs the Bureau of Labor and Industries to create certain guidance and informational mate-
rials to assist employers and employees.
Prohibits employers from denying an employee’s request to have [an authorized representative]
a support person accompany the employee in discussions concerning reasonable accommodation
subject to specific conditions.
Extends prohibition against discrimination in government services, programs and activities to
local governments.
Prohibits employers from using minimum physical requirements [to screen out persons with dis-
abilities] in a job posting without connecting the physical requirements to the essential
functions of the job.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to protections for persons with disabilities; creating new provisions; and amending ORS
3 659A.112, 659A.118 and 659A.142.
4 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
5 SECTION 1. Section 2 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of ORS 659A.103 to
6 659A.145.
7 SECTION 2. The Bureau of Labor and Industries shall create guidance and informational
8 materials to assist employers in complying with the provisions of ORS 659A.112, 659A.118 and
9 659A.121 concerning reasonable accommodation and to assist employees in understanding the
10 rights and protections provided under those sections. The bureau shall make the materials
11 available to employers on the bureau’s website.
12 SECTION 3. ORS 659A.112 is amended to read:
13 659A.112. (1) It is an unlawful employment practice for any employer to refuse to hire, employ
14 or promote, to bar or discharge from employment or to discriminate in compensation or in terms,
15 conditions or privileges of employment on the basis of disability.
16 (2) An employer violates subsection (1) of this section if the employer does any of the following:
17 (a) The employer limits, segregates or classifies a job applicant or employee in a way that ad-
18 versely affects the opportunities or status of the applicant or employee because the applicant or
19 employee has a disability.
20 (b) The employer participates in a contractual or other arrangement or relationship that has the
21 effect of subjecting a qualified job applicant or employee with a disability to the discrimination
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 239

A-Eng. HB 4093
1 prohibited by ORS 659A.112 to 659A.139, including but not limited to participating in a relationship
2 with an employment or referral agency, a labor union, an organization providing fringe benefits to
3 an employee of the employer, or an organization providing training and apprenticeship programs.
4 (c) The employer utilizes standards, criteria or methods of administration that have the effect
5 of discrimination on the basis of disability, or that perpetuate the discrimination of others who are
6 subject to common administrative control.
7 (d) The employer excludes or otherwise denies equal jobs or benefits to a qualified individual
8 because the individual is known to have a relationship or association with an individual with a
9 disability.
10 (e) The employer does not make reasonable accommodation to the known physical or mental
11 limitations of a qualified individual with a disability who is a job applicant or employee, unless the
12 employer can demonstrate that the accommodation would impose an undue hardship on the opera-
13 tion of the business of the employer.
14 (f) The employer denies employment opportunities to a job applicant or employee who is a
15 qualified individual with a disability, if the denial is based on the need of the employer to make
16 reasonable accommodation to the physical or mental impairments of the employee or applicant.
17 (g) The employer uses qualification standards, employment tests or other selection criteria, in-
18 cluding those based on an individual’s uncorrected vision or unaided hearing, that screen out or
19 tend to screen out an individual with a disability or a class of individuals with disabilities unless
20 the standard, test or other selection criterion, as used by the employer, is shown to be job-related
21 for the position in question and is consistent with business necessity.
22 (h) The employer fails to select and administer tests relating to employment in the most effective
23 manner to ensure that when the test is administered to a job applicant or employee who has a dis-
24 ability that impairs sensory, manual or speaking skills, the test results accurately reflect the skills,
25 aptitude or other characteristics of the applicant or employee that the test purports to measure,
26 rather than reflecting the impaired sensory, manual or speaking skills of the employee or applicant.
27 The provisions of this paragraph do not limit the ability of an employer to select or administer tests
28 designed to measure sensory, manual or speaking skills of an employee or job applicant.
29 (i) The employer uses minimum physical requirements set forth in a job posting without
30 connecting the physical requirements to the essential functions of the job.
31 SECTION 4. ORS 659A.118 is amended to read:
32 659A.118. (1) For the purposes of ORS 659A.112, reasonable accommodation may include:
33 (a) Making existing facilities used by employees readily accessible to and usable by individuals
34 with disabilities.
35 (b) Job restructuring, part-time or modified work schedules or reassignment to a vacant position.
36 (c) Acquisition or modification of equipment or devices.
37 (d) Appropriate adjustment or modification of examinations, training materials or policies.
38 (e) The provision of qualified readers or interpreters.
39 (2) An employer is not required to provide a reasonable accommodation to an individual who
40 satisfies the criteria for being an individual with a disability for the purposes of ORS 659A.103 to
41 659A.145 solely because the individual meets the criterion described in ORS 659A.104 (1)(c).
42 (3)(a) An employer may not deny an employee’s request to have a support person ac-
43 company the employee in any discussion over matters concerning reasonable accommo-
44 dation, provided that the support person:
45 (A) Does not disrupt or inhibit the discussion; and
[2]

A-Eng. HB 4093
1 (B) Agrees in advance to comply with the confidentiality requirements related to the
2 employee’s personal health information as described in paragraph (b) of this subsection, in-
3 cluding by written acknowledgment if required by the employer.
4 (b) An employer may require a support person to sign a written acknowledgment agree-
5 ing to keep confidential any of the employee’s personal health information that is revealed
6 during the course of the discussion, unless the employee consents to disclosure.
7 SECTION 5. ORS 659A.142 is amended to read:
8 659A.142. (1) As used in this section:
9 (a) “Health care facility” has the meaning given that term in ORS 442.015.
10 (b) “Health professional regulatory board” has the meaning given that term in ORS 676.160.
11 (c) “Local government” means any city, county, school district or other special district
12 in this state.
13 [(c)] (d) “Medical resources” includes but is not limited to:
14 (A) Medical devices or equipment.
15 (B) Prescription drugs.
16 (C) Laboratory testing.
17 [(d)] (e) “Provider” means:
18 (A) An individual licensed or certified by a health professional regulatory board.
19 (B) A health care facility.
20 [(e)] (f) “State government” has the meaning given that term in ORS 174.111.
21 (2) It is an unlawful employment practice for an employment agency to fail or refuse to refer for
22 employment, or otherwise discriminate against, any individual because that individual has a disa-
23 bility, or to classify or refer for employment any individual because that individual has a disability.
24 (3) It is an unlawful employment practice for a labor organization, because an individual has a
25 disability, to exclude or to expel from its membership such individual or to discriminate in any way
26 against such individual.
27 (4) It is an unlawful practice for any place of public accommodation, resort or amusement as
28 defined in ORS 659A.400, or any person acting on behalf of such place, to make any distinction,
29 discrimination or restriction because a customer or patron is an individual with a disability.
30 (5)(a) It is an unlawful practice for state or local government to exclude an individual from
31 participation in or deny an individual the benefits of the services, programs or activities of state
32 or local government or to make any distinction, discrimination or restriction because the individual
33 has a disability.
34 (b) Paragraph (a) of this subsection is intended to ensure equal access to available services,
35 programs and activities of state and local government.
36 (c) Paragraph (a) of this subsection is not intended to:
37 (A) Create an independent entitlement to any service, program or activity of state or local
38 government; or
39 (B) Require state or local government to take any action that state or local government can
40 demonstrate would result in a fundamental alteration in the nature of a service, program or activity
41 of state or local government or would result in undue financial or administrative burdens on state
42 or local government.
43 (6)(a) It is an unlawful practice for a provider or any person acting on behalf of a provider to
44 discriminate by doing any of the following based on the patient’s race, color, national origin, sex,
45 sexual orientation, gender identity, age or disability:
[3]

A-Eng. HB 4093
1 (A) Deny medical treatment to the patient that is likely to benefit the patient based on an in-
2 dividualized assessment of the patient using objective medical evidence; or
3 (B) Limit or restrict in any manner the allocation of medical resources to the patient.
4 (b) In determining whether medical treatment is likely to benefit a patient under paragraph
5 (a)(A) of this subsection, a provider shall consult with the patient and others legally authorized to
6 act on behalf of the patient, if available.
7 (c) This subsection does not:
8 (A) Restrict the authority of a patient, or an individual legally authorized to act on behalf of a
9 patient, to consent to or decline medical treatment;
10 (B) Require the provision of medical treatment that is prohibited by state or federal law; or
11 (C) Restrict a provider, after completing the individualized assessment described in paragraph
12 (a)(A) of this subsection and the consultation described in paragraph (b) of this subsection, from
13 providing objective information to the patient about the risks and benefits of treatment.
14 (7) Receipt or alleged receipt of treatment for a mental disorder does not constitute evidence
15 of an individual’s inability to acquire, rent or maintain property.
